metadata.name: Glossolalia #146
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: The Face We Had #193
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #318
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

metadata.name: Concrete #156
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Sublime #76
metadata.description:
We are always running, for a purpose/without a purpose; towards a goal/without a goal; mindfully/mindlessly, and we change; transformed by the situations surrounding us, transformed by our own footprints in our everyday lives. Sometimes its hard to look at our own selves, ashamed of the moth that we might have become. And sometimes we are proud, of the beautiful butterfly that we might have become. However, let us not forget that change is inevitable. And it lies within us - the power to change ourselves and how we allow ourselves to be shaped by the never ending feedback effects of our society. Let us all change for a better tomorrow. 

- - - - - - - - -

Energy can neither be created nor be destroyed. But it always changes from one form to the other. Starting with this half forgotten statement from my childhood school memories, driven by this idea of constant change as an invariance in all live systems - I present before you, Sublime. 

Made with love in cables.gl harnessing the power of noise!

Press & hold 'p' for performance.(The feedback system can be a bit heavy sometimes.)
Press 's' to save a screenshot.

metadata.name: MECHA BREATH #58
metadata.description:
A special collection for #objkt4objkt 2024

Taking a very simple concept and sticking to it. Here we divide a space in Voronoi cells, extrude the defined polygons in 3D, and then rotate them along one of the polygon's sides.
I was doing research on materials and lighting when I tried this and thought it had some generative merits, and then I heard of the event, so I decided to create a generator with it.
All the colors/tints come from the lights, environment and material properties, the volume themselves are always "white".

Best enjoyed on desktop / Chrome.

!!! Be sure the check the menu that you can find by clicking/tapping the BUTTON in the TOP LEFT !!!
In this menu you'll find some options to customize and experience the artwork, as well as the exports menu.

!!! TO EXPORT CLEAN HIGH RESOLUTION CAPTURES, click the "EXPORTS" button in the menu, select your desired resolution then click the "START CAPTURE" button. This only works when the generator is running in its own window, so be sure to click the "OPEN" button.
